*[[Seraiki language|Seraiki]]: 0.99%\n*Others: 1.49% \n\n===Religion===\nAccording to the 1998 census, the breakdown of the population by religion is as following:{{sfn|PCO|1999|p=32}}\n*[[Islam]]: 96.13%\n*[[Hinduism]]: 3.18%\n*[[Christianity]]: 0.51%\n*Others: 0.14%\n\n==Economy==\nSukkur's economy is largely reliant upon the agricultural produce from northern Sindh's farms, and serves as a trading and processing center for agricultural goods.<ref name=bowden><{{cite book|last1=Bowden|first1=Rob|title=Settlements of the Indus River|date=2004|publisher=Heinemann-Raintree Library|isbn=978-1403457189|url=https://books.google.com/?id=N3JKeIBYmoMC&dq=sukkur+established+by+british|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> The city also once had a bustling shipbuilding industry.<ref name=\"sukk\"/>\n\nSukkur is well-connected to the rest of Pakistan by road and rail, which in turn has attracted new industries such as chemical manufacturing, metalworking, and cement manufacturing.<ref name=bowden/>\n\n===Agriculture===\nSukkur had a large fertile and cultivable land area. During ''kharif'', rice, bajra, cotton, tomatoes and peas are cultivated; whereas during ''rabi'' the main crops are wheat, barley, graham and melons. Sukkur is famous, world over, for its dates. Sukkur also has a large Riveraine forest along the course of the Indus. These tropical forests are found within the protective embankments on either side of the Indus. During 1997\u201398 the total area under forests was 510&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> which yielded {{convert|55000|ft3|m3}} of timber and {{convert|27000|ft3|m3}} of [[firewood]] besides other mine products.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://sukkurcity.com/sites/about/sukkur_at_Glance.aspx|title = Sukku at A Glance|date = |accessdate = 18 September 2014|website = sukkurcity.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findpk.com/cities/Explorer-pakistan-Sukkur.html |title=Explore Pakistan |date= |access-date=18 September 2014 |website=findpk.com |publisher= |last= |first= |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708074930/http://findpk.com/cities/Explorer-pakistan-Sukkur.html |archive-date=8 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n===Road=== \nThe city will be connected to [[Multan]] by  [[M5 motorway (Pakistan)|M-5 motorway]], with onwards motorway connections to [[Lahore]], [[Islamabad]], and [[Peshawar]]. Sukkur will also be connected to [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]] by the [[M6 motorway (Pakistan)|M-6 motorway]], with onwards connections to Karachi via the [[M9 motorway (Pakistan)|M-9 motorway]]. The M-5 and M-6 are being built as part of the wider [[China-Pakistan Economic Corridor]].\n\n===Rail===\n[[Sukkur railway station]] serves as the city's main rail station. Passenger services are provided exclusively by [[Pakistan Railways]]. The city's station is serviced by the [[Jaffar Express]] that runs between [[Rawalpindi]] and [[Quetta]], the [[Sukkur Express]] that runs between [[Karachi]] and [[Jacobabad]], and the [[Akbar Express]] that runs between Quetta and [[Peshawar]].\n\n===Air===\n[[Sukkur Airport]], located 8&nbsp;km outside of the city, is served by [[Pakistan International Airlines]], with direct flights to [[Karachi]], [[Lahore]], and [[Islamabad]].\n\n==Administration==\nThe city of Sukkur is the capital of [[Sukkur Division]] and also Divisional and district headquarters. Tehsils (Talukas) and contains many [[Union Councils of Pakistan|Union council]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.lgdsindh.com.pk/tmasukkur6.htm\n |title       = Union Administrations of Taluka Sukkur\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060511170455/http://www.lgdsindh.com.pk/tmasukkur6.htm\n |archive-date = 11 May 2006\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref> Sukkur is home to one of three circuit benches of the [[Sindh High Court]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sindhhighcourt.gov.pk/Introduction.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-01-26 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126064106/http://www.sindhhighcourt.gov.pk/introduction.shtml |archive-date=26 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Sukkur IBA University - academic block I (2).jpg|thumb|The [[Sukkur IBA University]] is one of Pakistan's most highly ranked business schools.]]\nThe [[Sukkur IBA University]] (''previously'' '''Sukkur Institute of Business Administration''' or '''Sukkur IBA''') is a business school founded in 1994. The institute is ranked 3rd among the five independent business schools of Pakistan included in the Higher Education Commission Pakistan Business School Ranking-2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paked.net/higher_education/hec_university_rankings.htm|title=HEC University Rankings - Top Universities|website=www.paked.net}}</ref>\n\n[[Begum Nusrat Bhutto Women University]] is the public sector University exclusively for women. Established on 50 Acre of land at the [[Rohri]] Bypass [[N-5 National Highway|N-5]] [[National Highways of Pakistan|National Highway]]\n\nThe [[Aror University of Art, Architecture, Design and Heritages]] is established  near Sukkur at [[Rohri]] bypass [[N-5 National Highway]]. The University will offer the graduate, postgraduate an advance studies in the field of architecture, textile design, photography, interior design, communication design, ceramics and other disciplines.\n\nThe [[Ghulam Muhammad Mahar Medical College]] is a constituent College of [[Shaheed Mohtarma Benazir Bhutto Medical University]].<ref name=\"smbbmu.edu.pk\">{{cite web |url=http://beta.smbbmu.edu.pk/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-03-12 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112148/http://beta.smbbmu.edu.pk/ |archive-date=2 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Masum Shah|Mir Muhammad Masum Nami]] (d. 1606): Born to Shaikh-ul-Islam of [[#The fortress of Bhakkar|Bhakkar]] of that time. He authored ''Tarikh-i-Masumi'' (aka ''Tarikh-i-Sind''), a book on history of the Sindh province from the start of [[Muhammad Bin Qasim]]'s arrival in Sindh to the beginning of 17th century. ''Mufradat-i-Nami'' was book written on medicine by him. He wrote a ''Diwan'' of poetry and versified the translation of legend of ''Sassi Pannu''.{{sfn|Nabi Hadi|1995}}\n* [[Hemu Kalani]]\n* Sardar [[Ghulam Muhammad Khan Mahar]]\n* Syed [[Nasir Hussain Shah]]\n* [[Abdul Hafeez Pirzada]]\n* [[Syed Khurshid Ahmed Shah|Syed Khurshid Shah]], Leader of Opposition for National Assembly of Pakistan from June 2013 to May 2018\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alor (Sukkur)|Alor]] and [[Arora]]\n* [[Ghulam Muhammad Mahar Medical College]]\n* [[List of educational institutions in Sukkur]]\n* [[Sukkur IBA University]]\n* [[Begum Nusrat Bhutto Women University]]\n* [[Aror University of Art, Architecture, Design and Heritages]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|33em}}\n* {{citation |author=Dirk Collier|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=40ywDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT207|title=The Great Mughals and their India|date=1 March 2016|publisher=Hay House, Inc.|isbn=978-9-38-454498-0|p=207|ref={{sfnref|Dirk Collier|2016}}}}\n* {{citation |author=Nabi Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qjJmzdJFOHwC&pg=PA449|title=Dictionary of Indo-Persian Literature|date=1995|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-8-17-017311-3|p=449|ref={{sfnref|Nabi Hadi|1995}}}}\n* {{citation |author=James Wynbrandt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xQGwgJnCPZgC&pg=PA71|title=A Brief History of Pakistan|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-81-606184-6|p=71|ref={{sfnref|James Wynbrandt|2009}}}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sukkur}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n* [http://www.sukkur.gov.pk/default.asp District Government Sukkur]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140628105109/http://www.gmmmc.edu.pk/ Ghulam Muhammad Maher Medical College, Sukkur]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060307195652/http://www.adb.org/Documents/PCRs/PAK/IN229-01.pdf ADB Report on Sukkur Barrage 2001]\n* [https://nation.com.pk/11-Dec-2017/water-scarcity-in-pakistan-causes-effects-and-solutions An Overview of the History and Impacts of the Water Issue in Pakistan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060327065515/http://www.un.org.pk/undp/cpr/floods/summer-floods-update-no-6-26july05.doc Pakistan Floods Situation Report, 26 July 2005]\n\n{{PakistanCities}}\n{{Pakistan topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sukkur]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Sukkur District]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the district|Sukkur district|other uses|Sukkur (disambiguation)|and|Sukkar (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Sukkur\n| official_name =\n| native_name =<br/>{{hlist|{{lang|sd|\u0633\u06a9\u0631}}|{{lang|ur|{{nq|\u0633\u0643\u06be\u0631}}}}}}\n| settlement_type = [[Metropolis]]\n|image_skyline = File:Rohri.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|image_caption = View of Sukkur's iconic British-era [[Lansdowne Bridge Rohri|Lansdowne Bridge]] and the modern [[Ayub Bridge]], which both span the [[Indus River]] and offer access to the city of [[Rohri]]\n| image_map =\n| mapsize = \n| map_alt =\n| map_caption = Location of Sukkur\n| coordinates = {{Coord|27|42|22|N|68|50|54|E|type:city_region:PK|display=inline,title}}\n|image_blank_emblem = Sukkur Municipal Corporation.png\n| pushpin_map = Sindh#Pakistan\n| pushpin_label_position = <!-- left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_map_alt =\n| pushpin_mapsize =\n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = {{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Subdivisions of Pakistan|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Sindh]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Pakistan#Sindh|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Sukkur District]]\n| subdivision_type3 =  Taluka\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Sukkur Taluka]]\n| population_total = 551,357<ref>http://www.pbs.gov.pk/sites/default/files/PAKISTAN%20TEHSIL%20WISE%20FOR%20WEB%20CENSUS_2017.pdf</ref>\n| population_as_of = 2017\n| total_type=[[City]]\n| area_total_km2=85\n| area_metro_km2 = 5165\n| elevation_m = 67\n| elevation_m_min =\n| elevation_m_max =\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n|government_footnotes =\n|government_type = Municipal Corporation\n|leader_title = [[Mayor of Sukkur]]\n|leader_name = Arsalan Shaikh\n|title=\n|leader_title1 = [[Mayor of Sukkur|Deputy Mayor of Sukkur]]\n|leader_name1 = Tariq Chauhan\n|established_title = \n|established_date = 1862\n| blank_name_sec1 = Number of towns\n| blank_info_sec1 = 4\n| blank_name_sec2 = Number of [[Union councils of Pakistan|Union councils]]\n| blank_info_sec2 = 20\n| area_code = 071\n| area_code_type = [[List of dialling codes of Pakistan|Calling code]]\n| timezone1 = [[Pakistan Standard Time|PST]]\n| utc_offset1 = +5\n| website =\n| footnotes = {{cite web |url=http://www.sukkur.gov.pk |title=About District |website=District Government Sukkur |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209135824/http://www.sukkur.gov.pk/ |archive-date=9 February 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Sukkur''' ({{Lang-sd|\u0633\u06a9\u0631}}; {{Lang-ur|{{nq|\u0633\u0643\u06be\u0631}}}}) is a city in the [[Pakistan]]i province of [[Sindh]] along the western bank of the [[Indus River]], directly across from the historic city of [[Rohri]]. Sukkur is the 3rd largest city in Sindh after [[Karachi]] and [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]] and [[List of most populous cities in Pakistan|14th largest]] city in [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"citypopulation.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Pakistan-100T.html|title=Pakistan: Provinces and Major Cities - Population Statistics, Maps, Charts, Weather and Web Information|website=www.citypopulation.de}}</ref> '''New Sukkur''' was established during the British era alongside the village of Sukkur. Sukkur's hill, along with the hill on the river island of [[Bukkur]], form what is sometimes considered the \"Gate of Sindh\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burton|first1=Richard|title=Sindh and the Races That Inhabit the Valley of the Indus|date=1851|publisher=Asian Educational Services|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gO6pPmYjF5MC&pg=PA9&dq=sukkur+sindh#v=onepage&q=sukkur%20sindh&f=false|accessdate=19 December 2017|isbn=9788120607583}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Sukkur may derive from the [[Arabic]] word for \"sugar,\" ''shakkar'', in reference to the [[sugarcane]] fields that have historically been abundant in the region.<ref name=\"sukk\">{{cite web|title=History of Sukkur|url=http://oldsukkur.org/history_of_sukkur|website=Old Sukkur|publisher=Sindhi Association of India|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> This may be an allusion to the relative prosperity of the region at the time.  Others have suggested the name may derive from the word ''Sukh'', derived from a [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] word for \"comfort.\"<ref name=\"sukk\"/>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Untitled_(2_of_3).jpg|thumb|left|Sukkur's Shrine of [[Masum Shah]] and adjacent minaret dates from 1607.]]\nThe region around Sukkur has been inhabited for millennia. The ruins of [[Lakhueen-jo-daro]], located near an industrial park on the outskirts of Sukkur,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hyder|first1=Ali|title=Brief Description of Archaeological Sites and Monuments of Sindh|url=https://www.academia.edu/11300512|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> date from the [[Indus Valley Civilisation#Mature Harappan|Mature Harappan]] period of the [[Indus Valley Civilisation|Indus Valley Civilization]], between 2600 BCE and 1900 BCE.<ref>{{cite web|title=Collecting samples from a Lakhueen-jo-daro trial trench|url=http://ancient.sindh.ws/hphs/15.htm|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422174251/http://ancient.sindh.ws/hphs/15.htm|archive-date=2008-04-22|df=}}</ref>\n[[File:Temple Sadh Belo.jpg|thumb|left|Sukkur is home of the Hindu [[Sadh Belo]] shrine.]]\n\n\"Old Sukkur\" was initially a small village prior to the establishment of a military garrison in 1839. Sukkur was built on a low limestone ridge on the banks of the [[Indus River]].<ref name=ross>{{cite book|last1=Ross|first1=David|title=The land of the five rivers and Sindh|date=1883|publisher=Chapman and Hall|url=https://archive.org/details/landfiveriversa00rossgoog|quote=sukkur.|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> The city was once surrounded by groves of [[date palm]]s that were traditionally believed to have grown from the discarded date-pits from Arab invaders in the 8th century.<ref name=ross/>\n\nThe village of Sukkur was directly across from the larger town of [[Rohri]], which served as a busy port along the Indus by the 1200s, and was a major trading centre for agricultural produce.<ref name=bowden/> An 86 foot tall minaret was built at Sukkur's shrine of Mir [[Masum Shah]] in 1607.<ref name=\"ross\"/>\n\n===British===\n[[File:Landsdown Bridge, Sukkur, Sindh.jpg|thumb|Completed in 1889, the [[Lansdowne Bridge (Pakistan)|Lansdowne Bridge]] displays elements of British military architecture.]]\n[[File:Sukkur Barrage in daylight.jpg|thumb|The [[Sukkur Barrage]], completed in 1932, forms part of one of the world's largest irrigation projects.]]\nModern Sukkur, or '''New Sukkur''', was built during British rule alongside what was once a small village directly across from the historic city of [[Rohri]]. The British established a military garrison here in 1839,<ref name=william/> which was abandoned in 1845, though Sukkur continued to grow in importance as a trading center.<ref name=william>{{cite book|last1=Hughes|first1=Albert William|title=A Gazetteer of the Province of Sind|publisher=G. Bell and Sons|date=1876|url=https://archive.org/details/agazetteerprovi00unkngoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/agazetteerprovi00unkngoog/page/n712 677]|quote=aror .|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> The Sukkur Municipality was constituted in 1862.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Sukkur|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Sukkur|encyclopedia=Britannica|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nCompleted in 1889, Sukkur's [[Lansdowne Bridge Rohri|Lansdowne Bridge]] connects the Sukkur to [[Rohri]] across the Indus, and was one of the first bridges to cross the river. The bridge made the journey between [[Karachi]] and [[Multan]] easier. The bridge was built with two large pylons rather than a series of pillars extending across the river - a cutting-edge design for such an expansive span.<ref name=\"sukk\"/> The bridge was also made of metal, and features an unusual design.\n\nThe [[Sukkur Barrage]] (formally called [[Lloyd Barrage]]), built under the [[British Raj]] on the [[Indus River]], controls one of the largest irrigation systems in the world. It was designed by Sir Arnold Musto KCIE, and constructed under the overall direction of [[Sir Charlton Harrison]] between 1923 and 1932. The {{convert|5001|ft|m}} long barrage is made of yellow stone and steel and can water nearly 10 million acres (40,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) of farmland through its seven large canals.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dawn.com/news/1029295|title = Rule violations threaten Sukkur Barrage|date = 16 July 2013|accessdate = 26 August 2014|website = dawn.com|publisher = |last = Kiana|first = Khaleeq}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hpsukkur.brinkster.net/barrage.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330232609/http://hpsukkur.brinkster.net/barrage.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-03-30 |title=Sukku Barrage |date= |access-date= |website= |publisher= |last= |first= }}</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the [[Partition of British India]] in 1947, Sukkur's old town was home to about 10,000 residents, while New Sukkur was home to 80,000.<ref name=\"sukk\"/>\n\n===Modern===\nAfter the [[Partition of India|independence]] of [[Pakistan]] most of the city's Hindu population migrated to India though like much of Sindh, Sukkur did not experience the widespread rioting that occurred in Punjab and Bengal.<ref name=kumar>{{cite journal|last1=Kumar|first1=Priya|title=Sindh, 1947 and Beyond|journal=South Asia: Journal of South Asian Studies|volume=39|issue=4|date=2 December 2016|pages=773\u2013789|doi=10.1080/00856401.2016.1244752}}</ref> In all, less than 500 Hindu were killed in \nall of Sindh between 1947-48 as Sindhi Muslims largely resisted calls to turn against their Hindu neighbours.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chitkara|first1=M. G.|title=Mohajir's Pakistan|date=1996|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-8170247463|url=https://books.google.com/?id=w8lv8tMHE9AC&pg=PA8&dq=%22less+than+500+Hindus+were+killed+in+Sindh%22#v=onepage&q=%22less%20than%20500%20Hindus%20were%20killed%20in%20Sindh%22&f=false|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> Hindus did not flee Sukkur ''en masse'' until riots erupted in Karachi on 6 January 1948, which sowed fear in Sindh's Hindus despite the fact that the riots were local and regarded Sikh refugees from Punjab seeking refuge in Karachi.<ref name=kumar/> The Muslim refugees from India settled in Sukkur.\n\nThe [https://www.site.com.pk/wordpress/?page_id=1484 Sindh Industrial Trading Estate] in Sukkur was established in 1950. The [[Ayub Bridge]] was built in 1962, and spans the Indus River alongside the British-era Landsdowne Bridge. The city suffered major flooding during the [[2010 Pakistan floods]] which inundated large parts of the city.\n\n==Geography==\nThe small [[Eocene]] limestone outcropping upon which Sukkur was founded is the most significant land deformation on the vast plains along the Indus Valley in Sindh and Punjab.<ref name=\"johnF\">{{cite book|last1=Shroder Jr.|first1=John F.|title=Himalaya to the Sea: Geology, Geomorphology and the Quaternary|date=2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1134919772|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AfWJAgAAQBAJ&dq=sukkur|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> The outcropping is part of the \"Jacobabad-Khairpur High\" and [[Rohri Hills]].<ref name=\"johnF\"/> The outcropping, along with the similar outcropping on Bukkar Island are sometimes referred to as the \"Sukkur Gorge,\" and has historically served as the traditional northern boundary of Sindh.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Flint|first1=Eric|title=The Dance of Time|date=2006|publisher=Baen Books|isbn=978-1416509318|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sbDxkzAn6KMC&pg=PT351&dq=sukkur#v=onepage&q=sukkur&f=false|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nSukkur has a [[hot desert climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''BWh''), characterised by very hot and hazy summers with dry and cool winters. Sukkur is known for its extremely hot summers, and was described as the hottest city in [[British India]].<ref name=william/> Wind speed is low throughout the year, and sunshine is abundant. Summer is very hot as the temperature can reach {{convert|50|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}}. Dry heat is experienced starting April to early June until the [[Monsoon]] season starts to arrive. Monsoons in Sukkur are not very wet, but bring high [[dew point]]s, resulting in high heat indices. Monsoons recede by September, but it is not until late October that the short lived autumn season is experienced before the onset of the region's cool winters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wunderground.com/history/daily/OPSK/date/2013-7-6?mr=1|title=Sukkur, Pakistan History|website=Weather Underground}}</ref> \n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Sukkur \n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 31.0\n|Feb record high C = 38.0\n|Mar record high C = 45.0\n|Apr record high C = 49.0\n|May record high C = 50.5\n|Jun record high C = 50.5\n|Jul record high C = 46.5\n|Aug record high C = 44.5\n|Sep record high C = 43.5\n|Oct record high C = 41.6\n|Nov record high C = 37.2\n|Dec record high C = 31.0\n|Jan high C = 24.8\n|Feb high C = 26.2\n|Mar high C = 32.4\n|Apr high C = 39.2\n|May high C = 43.3\n|Jun high C = 43.2\n|Jul high C = 41.0\n|Aug 